<br>
------------------<br>
First off .. it needs to be stated that this AI change was NOT tested. It was never on the Test Server, you never had a chance to see the results of this change in a live players environment. Sooo .. right there is mistake number one. You made a fundamental change to HEALING without even testing the results.<br>
<br>
Number two .. I'm assuming the intended result of this change was to reduce dependancy of players on clerics, AND to make the Velious boss mob encouters MORE difficult, and thus keep their player base longer (a fact already alluded to in one of Absor's previous replies in another thread) .. here's the reality.<br>
<br>
These encounters were hardly trivial prior to this change. On E'ci mobs such as Velketor, Yelinak, etc, are not killed .. and this is not for lack of trying. One guild has killed Velketor, that's it .. and they accomplished that using massive in fight res tactics, and everyone involved died multiple times. Yelinak has not died .. Zlandicar has not died .. Dain has not died other than pooding .. These were NOT encounters that are universally easy.<br>
<br>
That being said .. I can tell you, from my personal expierence at this level of the game at least, divine light and nature's touch and other such fixed heals will not work. Mobs that quad for 800 per swing cannot be countered with heals of that nature. The Mob can deal damage faster than those minor heals are capable of reversing it. That forced players to learn how to use and abuse Complete Heal, or in some select encounters Group Heals .. which is WHY clerics were and still ARE the primary healing class, and are NOT replacable.<br>
<br>
These are not frogs in sebelis, these are encounters that push the limits of what players can accomplish .. to win, players MUST use the MOST EFFEICIENT tactics, anything else will fall short. Clerics STILL are the MOST EFFECIENT Healers .. Warriors STILL are the MOST EFFICIENT Tanks .. Rogues STILL are the MOST EFFICIENT damage dealers. Nothing has changed.<br>
<br>
What HAS changed, is a specific nerf designed to counter these tactics, namely messing with mob hate in regards to debuffs and healing. Now, the warrior cannot tank effectively .. the rogue cannot deal max damage effecitvely .. and the cleric cannot HEAL effectively. In one patch you struck down all THREE area's.<br>
<br>
Like I said, the intended result I'm sure was to add difficulty to encounters, and to move the game away from class dependancy. The ACTUAL result, is you have indeed accomplished what you wanted to as far as reduction of capabilities, but the game has nothing to replace it. You have taken, without giving back. <br>
<br>
You can debate this Verant .. say no, we haven't done that. You can say it's too early for players to make these kind of assertions. I played enough yesterday to see exactly what is the results of this. We had a slight mixup on a Trak raid and ended up with the Sebelite Protector and 7 Juggernauts in our camp at the same time .. the end result? 7 Purple corpses on the ground .. the only other player casulty was a warrior and an enchanter. We won, but as could be expected, nearly every cleric died. After trak was dead .. what was the result? A bunch of purple corpses on the ground, due SPECIFCALLY to Trakanon agroing on them and killing them with melee, using the same tactics they previously did that did not get them killed.<br>
<br>
This is not a matter of learning new tactics, this is a matter of learning new limits. Certain encounters have essentially become undoable without use of MORONIC tactics involving in-battle ressing and multiple deaths per player per encounter. If THAT is your vision for EQ, well .. let me know, cause I'm not interested heh.<br>
